snippet.textDisplay:
LG OLED can't reach high global brightness because of EU energy regulation, which killed Plasma technology too (400w + in 3D) but AFAIK, OLED can reach DCI P3 99%+ and REC2020 72%.
Too bad Apple once again designed a screen like this.
Thunderbolt 3 is pumping 40Gbps for all peripherals down the chain, HDMI 2 on itself requires 48Gbps. (Maybe 6K RGB 12bits @60 doesn't need so much after all)
Bootcamp utility on windows is quite bad. You need it if you're using the mighty aluminium usb extended keyboard in order to retrieve missing keys like Insert, using different Fn combination keys. And it screws up capabilities for Windows to make a software raid. Without Bootcamp, it's a headache to use F1-F19 keys.
Great promise, so much disillusionment

snippet.textDisplay:
For all this monitor has an undoubtedly excellent panel and driving hardware, it bugs me that people keep letting Apple off with the direct comparison between this and the $30k monitors.
Those monitors have a bunch of connectivity (multiple SDI usually) and built in LUT switchers and so forth, plus often being ruggedised for use somewhere other than a post production office.
It's like comparing a flip phone to a smartphone. Sure they both can make excellent phonecalls and the flip phone is hella cheaper, but you wouldn't really mark them as direct competitors.
